<title>USA: U.S. will work for EU meat accord - USDA's Glickman.</title>
<headline>U.S. will work for EU meat accord - USDA's Glickman.</headline>
<dateline>WASHINGTON 1997-04-01</dateline>
<text>
<p>U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said Tuesday the United States would continue to try and reach an accord with the European Union over meat inspection procedures.</p>
<p>&quot;We intend to continue to work to reach an acceptable agreement in the coming months and to minimize trade disruptions to the extent possible,&quot; Glickman said in a statement.</p>
<p>He also reiterated statements by his trade advisor that EU slaughter plants will have to meet U.S. inspection standards, known as the HAACP standards, beginning on April 1.</p>
<p>Glickman said that the inspection standards could have an &quot;adverse effect&quot; on EU meat exports to the United States, which total some $300 million annually.</p>
<p>Negotiators have tried for nearly three years to reach an agreement on so-called veterinary equivalency standards.</p>
<p>Earlier Tuesday, USDA senior trade advisor Paul Drazek said the agency would also no longer provide export certificates for poultry, dairy and egg shipments to the EU. Drazek told reporters that the negotiations with the EU would continue over the coming weeks.</p>
<p>((--Washington commodities desk, 202-898-8300))</p>
